[
  {
    "lesson_id": "047",
    "trigger_word": "arbaro",
    "title": "LESSON 47: COMPOUND TENSES",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Combine ESTI with participles to create",
          "nuanced compound tenses.",
          "",
          "PROGRESSIVE (ongoing action):",
          "Mi estas leganta. = I am reading.",
          "Mi estis leganta. = I was reading.",
          "Mi estos leganta. = I will be reading.",
          "",
          "PERFECT (completed action):",
          "Mi estas leginta. = I have read.",
          "Mi estis leginta. = I had read.",
          "Mi estos leginta. = I will have read.",
          "",
          "PASSIVE COMPOUND:",
          "La libro estas legita. = The book is read.",
          "La libro estis legata. = It was being read.",
          "",
          "These create precise time distinctions!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek sep"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "048",
    "trigger_word": "pikniko",
    "title": "LESSON 48: WORD DERIVATION",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "Every Esperanto word can change its part of",
          "speech just by changing the ending!",
          "",
          "FROM ONE ROOT:",
          "bel- (root meaning \"beauty\")",
          "bela    = beautiful (adjective -a)",
          "bele    = beautifully (adverb -e)",
          "belo    = beauty (noun -o)",
          "beli    = to be beautiful (verb -i)",
          "",
          "vera (true) → vere (truly) → vero (truth)",
          "varma (warm) → varme (warmly) → varmo (warmth)",
          "",
          "ADD AFFIXES TOO:",
          "belega   = gorgeous (-eg- augmentative)",
          "beligi   = to beautify (-ig- causative)",
          "beleco   = beauty (abstract quality -ec-)",
          "One root, infinite possibilities!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek ok"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "049",
    "trigger_word": "respondeco",
    "title": "LESSON 49: THE '-END-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -END- means \"must be done\" or",
          "\"to be done\" (necessity/obligation).",
          "",
          "OBLIGATION:",
          "fari    → farenda     = do → to be done",
          "pagi    → pagenda     = pay → to be paid",
          "legi    → legenda     = read → to be read",
          "lerni   → lernenda    = learn → to be learned",
          "",
          "COMPARE WITH -IND-:",
          "-ind- = WORTH doing (value judgment)",
          "-end- = MUST BE done (necessity)",
          "leginda = worth reading (optional)",
          "legenda = must be read (required)",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "La raporto estas farenda ĝis vendredo.",
          "(The report must be done by Friday.)"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvardek naŭ"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "050",
    "trigger_word": "butono",
    "title": "LESSON 50: THE '-UM-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -UM- has NO fixed meaning! It's",
          "the \"wildcard\" suffix for words that don't",
          "fit other patterns. Learn by usage.",
          "",
          "COMMON -UM- WORDS:",
          "plena   → plenumi    = full → to fulfill",
          "kolo    → kolumi     = neck → collar",
          "butono  → butonumi   = button → to button up",
          "aero    → aerumi     = air → to air out",
          "brako   → brakumi    = arm → to embrace/hug",
          "okulo   → okulumi    = eye → to ogle/flirt",
          "komuna  → komunumo   = common → community",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Mi plenumis mian promeson.",
          "(I fulfilled my promise.)",
          "",
          "-UM- means \"do something related to\"!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvindek"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "051",
    "trigger_word": "plibonigi",
    "title": "LESSON 51: THE 'EKS-' PREFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The prefix EKS- means \"former\" or \"ex-\"",
          "It indicates something no longer current.",
          "",
          "FORMER RELATIONSHIPS:",
          "edzo → eksedzo = husband → ex-husband",
          "edzino → eksedzino = wife → ex-wife",
          "amiko → eksamiko = friend → ex-friend",
          "",
          "FORMER POSITIONS/STATUS:",
          "prezidento → eksprezidento = ex-president",
          "membro → eksmembro = member → former member",
          "soldato → ekssoldato = soldier → ex-soldier",
          "studento → eksstudento = student → ex-student",
          "",
          "IN USE:",
          "Mia eksedzo loĝas en Parizo.",
          "(My ex-husband lives in Paris.)",
          "EKS- works with any noun for roles/status!"
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvindek unu"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "lesson_id": "052",
    "trigger_word": "paŭzejo",
    "title": "LESSON 52: THE '-EG-' SUFFIX",
    "header_color": "green",
    "pages": [
      {
        "page": 1,
        "total_pages": 1,
        "content": [
          "The suffix -EG- amplifies things!",
          "",
          "MAKING THINGS BIG:",
          "domo    → domego     = house → mansion",
          "vento   → ventego    = wind → storm",
          "bona    → bonega     = good → excellent",
          "",
          "INTENSIFYING:",
          "malsata → malsatega  = hungry → starving",
          "venki   → venkegi    = win → trounce",
          "ami     → amegi      = love → adore",
          "",
          "-EG- is the opposite of -ET-:",
          "dometo (cottage) <-> domego (mansion)",
          "",
          "There are a lot of suffixes in Esperanto. To",
          "help remember this one particularly, try",
          "thinking 'EGZAGERATE'."
        ],
        "pronunciation": "Leciono kvindek du"
      }
    ]
  }
]
